{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} Then thou shalt bring her home to thine house, and she shall shave her head, and pare her nails;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} And she shall put the raiment of her captivity from off her, and shall remain in thine house, and bewail her father and her mother a full month:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} And after that thou shalt go in unto her, and be her husband, and she shall be thy wife.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|7}} And it shall be, if thou have no delight in her, then thou shalt let her go whither she will;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|8}} But thou shalt not sell her at all for money, thou shalt not make merchandise of her, because thou hast humbled her.

===Levirite Marriage===
:''(from Deuteronomy 25:5-10)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} If brethren dwell together, and one of them die, and have no child, the wife of the dead shall not marry without unto a stranger:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Her husband's brother shall go in unto her, and take her to him to wife, and perform the duty of an husband's brother unto her.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} And it shall be, that the firstborn which she beareth shall succeed in the name of his brother which is dead,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} That his name be not put out of Israel.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} And if the man like not to take his brother's wife, then let his brother's wife go up to the gate unto the elders, and say,

:{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} My husband's brother refuseth to raise up unto his brother a name in Israel, he will not perform the duty of my husband's brother.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} Then the elders of his city shall call him, and speak unto him: and if he stand to it, and say, I like not to take her;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|7}} Then shall his brother's wife come unto him in the presence of the elders,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|8}} And loose his shoe from off his foot, and spit in his face, and shall answer and say,

:{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} So shall it be done unto that man that will not build up his brother's house.

:{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|B}} And his name shall be called in Israel,

::{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|i}} The house of him that hath his shoe loosed.
	
===Virgin Wives===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:13-21)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} If any man take a wife, and go in unto her, and hate her,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} And give occasions of speech against her, and bring up an evil name upon her, and say,

:{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} I took this woman, and when I came to her, I found her not a maid:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} Then shall the father of the damsel, and her mother,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} Take and bring forth the tokens of the damsel's virginity unto the elders of the city in the gate:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} And the damsel's father shall say unto the elders,

:{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} I gave my daughter unto this man to wife, and he hateth her;

:{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|B}} And, lo, he hath given occasions of speech against her, saying,

::{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|i}} I found not thy daughter a maid;

:{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|C}} And yet these are the tokens of my daughter's virginity.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} And they shall spread the cloth before the elders of the city.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|7}} And the elders of that city shall take that man and chastise him;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|8}} And they shall amerce him in an hundred shekels of silver, and give them unto the father of the damsel,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|9}} Because he hath brought up an evil name upon a virgin of Israel: and she shall be his wife; he may not put her away all his days.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|10}} But if this thing be true, and the tokens of virginity be not found for the damsel:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|11}} Then they shall bring out the damsel to the door of her father's house, and the men of her city shall stone her with stones that she die:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|12}} Because she hath wrought folly in Israel, to play the whore in her father's house: so shalt thou put evil away from among you.

===Adultery===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:22)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} If a man be found lying with a woman married to an husband, then they shall both of them die,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Both the man that lay with the woman, and the woman: so shalt thou put away evil from Israel.

===Betrothal===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:23-27)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} If a damsel that is a virgin be betrothed unto an husband, and a man find her in the city, and lie with her;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Then ye shall bring them both out unto the gate of that city, and ye shall stone them with stones that they die;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} The damsel, because she cried not, being in the city; and the man, because he hath humbled his neighbour's wife:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} So thou shalt put away evil from among you.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} But if a man find a betrothed damsel in the field, and the man force her, and lie with her: then the man only that lay with her shall die.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} But unto the damsel thou shalt do nothing; there is in the damsel no sin worthy of death:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|7}} For as when a man riseth against his neighbour, and slayeth him, even so is this matter:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|8}} For he found her in the field, and the betrothed damsel cried, and there was none to save her.

===Fornication===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:28-29)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} If a man find a damsel that is a virgin, which is not betrothed, and lay hold on her, and lie with her, and they be found;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Then the man that lay with her shall give unto the damsel's father fifty shekels of silver, and she shall be his wife;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} Because he hath humbled her, he may not put her away all his days.

===Incest===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:28-30)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} A man shall not take his father's wife, nor discover his father's skirt.

===Divorce===
:''(from Deuteronomy 24:1-5)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} When a man hath taken a wife, and married her,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} And it come to pass that she find no favour in his eyes, because he hath found some uncleanness in her:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} Then let him write her a bill of divorcement, and give it in her hand, and send her out of his house.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} And when she is departed out of his house, she may go and be another man's wife.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} And if the latter husband hate her, and write her a bill of divorcement, and giveth it in her hand, and sendeth her out of his house;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} Or if the latter husband die, which took her to be his wife;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|7}} Her former husband, which sent her away, may not take her again to be his wife, after that she is defiled;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|8}} For that is abomination before the LORD: and thou shalt not cause the land to sin, which the LORD thy God giveth thee for an inheritance.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|9}} When a man hath taken a new wife, he shall not go out to war, neither shall he be charged with any business:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|10}} But he shall be free at home one year, and shall cheer up his wife which he hath taken.

==Promises==
===Vows===
:''(from Deuteronomy 23:21-23)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} When thou shalt vow a vow unto the LORD thy God, thou shalt not slack to pay it:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} For the LORD thy God will surely require it of thee; and it would be sin in thee.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} But if thou shalt forbear to vow, it shall be no sin in thee.
 
{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} That which is gone out of thy lips thou shalt keep and perform;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} Even a freewill offering, according as thou hast vowed unto the LORD thy God, which thou hast promised with thy mouth.
===Pledges of security===
:''(from Deuteronomy 24:10-13 and Deuteronomy 24:6)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} When thou dost lend thy brother any thing, thou shalt not go into his house to fetch his pledge.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Thou shalt stand abroad, and the man to whom thou dost lend shall bring out the pledge abroad unto thee.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} And if the man be poor, thou shalt not sleep with his pledge:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} In any case thou shalt deliver him the pledge again when the sun goeth down, that he may sleep in his own raiment, and bless thee:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} And it shall be righteousness unto thee before the LORD thy God.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} No man shall take the nether or the upper millstone to pledge: for he taketh a man's life to pledge.

===Usury===
:''(from Deuteronomy 23:19-20)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} Thou shalt not lend upon usury to thy brother; usury of money, usury of victuals, usury of any thing that is lent upon usury:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Unto a stranger thou mayest lend upon usury; but unto thy brother thou shalt not lend upon usury:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} That the LORD thy God may bless thee in all that thou settest thine hand to in the land whither thou goest to possess it.

==Ownership==
===The year of debt cancellation ===
:''(from Deuteronomy 15:1-18)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} At the end of every seven years thou shalt make a release.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} And this is the manner of the release: Every creditor that lendeth ought unto his neighbour shall release it;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} He shall not exact it of his neighbour, or of his brother; because it is called the LORD's release.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} Of a foreigner thou mayest exact it again: but that which is thine with thy brother thine hand shall release;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} Save when there shall be no poor among you;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} For the LORD shall greatly bless thee in the land which the LORD thy God giveth thee for an inheritance to possess it:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|7}} Only if thou carefully hearken unto the voice of the LORD thy God, to observe to do all these commandments which I command thee this day.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} For the LORD thy God blesseth thee, as he promised thee:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|B}} And thou shalt lend unto many nations, but thou shalt not borrow;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|C}} And thou shalt reign over many nations, but they shall not reign over thee.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|8}} If there be among you a poor man of one of thy brethren within any of thy gates in thy land which the LORD thy God giveth thee,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} Thou shalt not harden thine heart, nor shut thine hand from thy poor brother:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|B}} But thou shalt open thine hand wide unto him, and shalt surely lend him sufficient for his need, in that which he wanteth.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|9}} Beware that there be not a thought in thy wicked heart, saying,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} The seventh year, the year of release, is at hand;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|B}} And thine eye be evil against thy poor brother, and thou givest him nought;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|C}} And he cry unto the LORD against thee, and it be sin unto thee.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|D}} Thou shalt surely give him, and thine heart shall not be grieved when thou givest unto him:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|E}} Because that for this thing the LORD thy God shall bless thee in all thy works, and in all that thou puttest thine hand unto.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|F}} For the poor shall never cease out of the land: therefore I command thee, saying,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|10}} Thou shalt open thine hand wide unto thy brother, to thy poor, and to thy needy, in thy land.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|11}} And if thy brother, an Hebrew man, or an Hebrew woman, be sold unto thee, and serve thee six years;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} Then in the seventh year thou shalt let him go free from thee.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|B}} And when thou sendest him out free from thee, thou shalt not let him go away empty:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|C}} Thou shalt furnish him liberally out of thy flock, and out of thy floor, and out of thy winepress:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|D}} Of that wherewith the LORD thy God hath blessed thee thou shalt give unto him.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|12}} And thou shalt remember that thou wast a bondman in the land of Egypt, and the LORD thy God redeemed thee:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|13}} Therefore I command thee this thing to day.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|14}} And it shall be, if he say unto thee, I will not go away from thee; because he loveth thee and thine house, because he is well with thee;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} Then thou shalt take an aul, and thrust it through his ear unto the door, and he shall be thy servant for ever.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|B}} And also unto thy maidservant thou shalt do likewise.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|15}} It shall not seem hard unto thee, when thou sendest him away free from thee;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|A}} For he hath been worth a double hired servant to thee, in serving thee six years:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|B}} And the LORD thy God shall bless thee in all that thou doest.

===False weights and measures===
:''(from Deuteronomy 25:13-16)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} Thou shalt not have in thy bag divers weights, a great and a small.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Thou shalt not have in thine house divers measures, a great and a small.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} But thou shalt have a perfect and just weight, a perfect and just measure shalt thou have:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} That thy days may be lengthened in the land which the LORD thy God giveth thee.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} For all that do such things, and all that do unrighteously, are an abomination unto the LORD thy God.

===Boundary stones===
:''(from Deuteronomy 19:14)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} Thou shalt not remove thy neighbour's landmark, which they of old time have set in thine inheritance,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Which thou shalt inherit in the land that the LORD thy God giveth thee to possess it.

===Lost property===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:1-4)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} Thou shalt not see thy brother's ox or his sheep go astray, and hide thyself from them:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Thou shalt in any case bring them again unto thy brother.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} And if thy brother be not nigh unto thee, or if thou know him not, then thou shalt bring it unto thine own house,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} And it shall be with thee until thy brother seek after it, and thou shalt restore it to him again.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} In like manner shalt thou do with his ass; and so shalt thou do with his raiment;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} And with all lost thing of thy brother's, which he hath lost, and thou hast found, shalt thou do likewise: thou mayest not hide thyself.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|7}} Thou shalt not see thy brother's ass or his ox fall down by the way, and hide thyself from them:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|8}} Thou shalt surely help him to lift them up again.

===Servants===
====Treatment====
:''(from Deuteronomy 24:14-15)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} Thou shalt not oppress an hired servant that is poor and needy,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Whether he be of thy brethren, or of thy strangers that are in thy land within thy gates:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} At his day thou shalt give him his hire, neither shall the sun go down upon it;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} For he is poor, and setteth his heart upon it:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} Lest he cry against thee unto the LORD, and it be sin unto thee.

====Fleeing servants====
:''(from Deuteronomy 23:15-16)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} Thou shalt not deliver unto his master the servant which is escaped from his master unto thee:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} He shall dwell with thee, even among you, in that place which he shall choose in one of thy gates, where it liketh him best:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} Thou shalt not oppress him.

====Kidnapping for slavery ====
:''(from Deuteronomy 24:7)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} If a man be found stealing any of his brethren of the children of Israel, and maketh merchandise of him, or selleth him;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} Then that thief shall die; and thou shalt put evil away from among you.

===Inheritance===
====The firstborn son====
:''(from Deuteronomy 21:15-17)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} If a man have two wives, one beloved, and another hated, and they have born him children, both the beloved and the hated;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} And if the firstborn son be hers that was hated:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} Then it shall be, when he maketh his sons to inherit that which he hath,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} That he may not make the son of the beloved firstborn before the son of the hated, which is indeed the firstborn:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} But he shall acknowledge the son of the hated for the firstborn, by giving him a double portion of all that he hath:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} For he is the beginning of his strength; the right of the firstborn is his.

====Levites====
:''(from Deuteronomy 18:1-8)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} The priests the Levites, and all the tribe of Levi, shall have no part nor inheritance with Israel:

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} They shall eat the offerings of the LORD made by fire, and his inheritance.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|3}} Therefore shall they have no inheritance among their brethren: the LORD is their inheritance, as he hath said unto them.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|4}} And this shall be the priest's due from the people, from them that offer a sacrifice, whether it be ox or sheep;

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|5}} And they shall give unto the priest the shoulder, and the two cheeks, and the maw.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|6}} The firstfruit also of thy corn, of thy wine, and of thine oil, and the first of the fleece of thy sheep, shalt thou give him.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|7}} For the LORD thy God hath chosen him out of all thy tribes, to stand to minister in the name of the LORD, him and his sons for ever.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|8}} And if a Levite come from any of thy gates out of all Israel, where he sojourned,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|9}} And come with all the desire of his mind unto the place which the LORD shall choose;
 
{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|10}} Then he shall minister in the name of the LORD his God, as all his brethren the Levites do, which stand there before the LORD.

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|11}} They shall have like portions to eat, beside that which cometh of the sale of his patrimony.

==Manufacture==
===Clothes===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:12)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} Thou shalt make thee fringes upon the four quarters of thy vesture, wherewith thou coverest thyself.
===New Houses===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:8)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} When thou buildest a new house, then thou shalt make a battlement for thy roof,

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|2}} That thou bring not blood upon thine house, if any man fall from thence.

===Mixing types===
:''(from Deuteronomy 22:9-11)''

{{font|size=smaller|color=#0000FF|1}} Thou shalt not sow thy vineyard with divers seeds: lest the fruit of thy seed which thou hast sown, and the fruit of thy vineyard, be defiled.

